data.title: Washington County Maps: Interactive History & Complete List
data.meta_description: This article looks into the varied maps of Washington. Discover the history and evolution of the State's Counties and the maps that tell their story.
data.text:
Maps of Washington are generally an important element of genealogy and family history research projects, notably in case you live far from where your ancestor resided. Since Washington’s political borders often changed, historic maps are significant in helping you find out the exact, specific location of your ancestor’s hometown, what land they owned, just who his or her neighbors happen to be, what the boundaries of their areas were, and a lot more.

Maps of Washington State are generally an excellent source for getting started with your own research, given that they provide substantially valuable information and give you facts quickly in a clearly presented and organized form. Maps of Washington are a major resource containing considerable amounts of rich detail regarding family history.

Washington borders Idaho, Oregon, and Canada. Washington’s 10 largest cities are Seattle, Spokane, Tacoma, Vancouver, Bellevue, Everett, Kent, Yakima, Renton, and Spokane Valley.

Learn more fascinating historical facts about Washington Counties here.

List of Every Washington County

Adams County

Established in 1883, Adams County has a population of approximately 19,000 residents. It is known for its agricultural industry and is home to the Othello Sand Dunes, a popular recreation area.

Asotin County was established in 1883 and has a population of around 23,000 people. It is located in the southeast corner of the state and is known for its outdoor recreation opportunities, including fishing and hiking.
